Polish Bankruptcy dataset - Danyah Khan¶

The overall problem we are trying to solve is whether we can use the finances of a company to predict whether a company is at risk of going bankrupt. This is important for companies that want to know the future of their company. They might have been successful at one point, but have hit a turning point for the worse and are trying to figure out if their company is too much in losses and will go bankrupt. The solution is valuable because the company can be prepared to go bankrupt or they can take a risk and work towards getting their company out of bankruptcy.

Reducing costs increases profitability, but only if sales prices and number of sales remain constant. However, if a company can efficiently cut costs without affecting quality, sales price, or sales figures, then that provides a path to higher profitability (Maverick 2020)

I'm answering the following research question, can the sales and costs be used for evaluating the company's profitability in that year? So, we will examine the features related to sales and costs compared to the orginal.

Also, my runtime for the grid search was really high and there were some errors with the memory allocation, so I had to manually test out different hyperparameters. Research: https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/122214/company-it-more-important-lower-costs-or-increase-revenue.asp#:~:text=Impact%20of%20Reducing%20Costs,number%20of%20sales%20remain%20constant.&text=However%2C%20if%20a%20company%20can,a%20path%20to%20higher%20profitability.

Although the gradient boost model performed better on the entire dataset, the gradient boost on the subset data related to costs and sales saw a decrease in performance. There is also much more overfitting going on in the model.

Conclusions¶

After testing out the different models and even trying out subsetting the data for sales and cost, the best model turned out to be the decision tree on the entire scaled dataset. The train set had an accuracy of 70% and the test set had an accuracy of 68%. The confusion matrix showed that there were a lot of false negatives, however compared to the other models, it was on the lower side.

Overall, the sales and cost subset data can be used to evaluate the profitability of a company and also to predict whether a company will go bankrupt or not. However, there could also be other ways of evaluating the profitability of a company that does not require a machine learning approach, such as the companies finance trends over time, and business and marketing strategies.
